article.description:
Tamika Whitmore scored 22 points to help the
Indiana Fever beat the Houston Comets 60-56 on Sunday night.
article.headline: Whitmore, Fever heat up late against fizzling Comets
article.linkText: Whitmore, Fever heat up late against fizzling Comets
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Tamika Whitmore returned to her All-Star
level of play as the Indiana Fever beat the Houston Comets 60-56 on
Sunday night.

Whitmore scored 22 points on 10-for-16 shooting. The Fever's
leading scorer shot 3-for-15 Saturday against Charlotte.

"Whit's not going to have two or three bad shooting games in a
row," Indiana coach Brian Winters said. "She showed a lot of
mental toughness and grit."

Tamika Catchings had 11 points and 10 rebounds, and Eboni
Hoffman added 11 points for the Fever (14-8).

Catchings wasn't sure how the Achilles tendinitis that kept her
out of the All-Star Game would hold up in a back-to-back situation.
She produced her fifth double-double of the season.

"I was a little bit concerned," she said. "It was bothering
me a lot before the game. I didn't say anything because I didn't
want coach to limit me. ... You put it behind you."

Sheryl Swoopes led Houston with 15 points and Tamecka Dixon
added 14. Mistie Williams finished with 11 points and a career-high
12 rebounds.

Indiana outscored Houston 22-14 in the fourth quarter to win
game one of a five-game homestand.

"You never want to lose at home," Whitmore said, "and with
this homestand, we want to send a message to those coming in: They
won't leave Conseco with a victory."

Houston (13-10) has lost four of its last five games and entered
the game short-handed.

Top scorer Tina Thompson missed her third straight game with a
strained right calf. Dominique Canty, who scored 24 points for
Houston the last time the teams played, sat out with a broken
finger.

Dixon drained a short jumper as time expired in the first
quarter, but Indiana still led 19-16.

Houston's stars got off to a rough start. All-Star center
Michelle Snow picked up three fouls in the first half and Swoopes
didn't score until she made a short jumper with 2:02 left in the
first half. She followed that with a 3-pointer that cut Indiana's
halftime lead to 27-25.

Both teams shot 37 percent before the break.

Dixon scored on a 3-point play with 1:25 left in the third
quarter to give Houston a 40-38 lead. Snow followed with a putback
basket to give the Comets a 42-38 lead at the end of the period.

"I thought when we had the opportunity to lead, we would have
capitalized better," Swoopes said. "We started having crucial
turnovers and giving up rebounds at crucial times. The game was
there for us to take back home."
